 #Introduction

In the highly competitive global logistics market, businesses must use advanced analytical tools to improve operations, reduce expenses and boost customer satisfaction. Thanks to simulation techniques which provides an effective way to model complex systems. Organisations can test strategies, predict outcomes and make data-driven decisions without taking on the risks associated with real-world experimentation. Because of its adaptability and ability to simulate highly dynamic systems, simulation is one of the most widely used methods in operations research (Law, 2015). Simulation is a fundamental tool for modern logistics management because it generates a digital representation of a real-world system, enabling analysts to experiment under various conditions without disrupting with actual operations (Banks et al., 2010).
In the case of Yellowstone Inc., a logistics firm that specialises in dependable and quick package deliveries, my report looks at the application of simulation techniques. The company's operational challenges include warehouse management, route optimisation and delivery time prediction in a situation of unpredictable traffic. These issues are typical of the more general problems faced by the global logistics industry, where supply chain risk, rising fuel prices and growing customer expectations demand ever more complex analytical techniques. Yellowstone Inc. can actively handle these pressures by using simulation, which allows management to analyse the potential effects of strategic choices before allocating resources in a real-world operational setting.
Three main tasks make up the structure of my report. The theoretical foundations of simulation are examined in Task 1, along with the important part that visualisation plays in explaining simulation results to stakeholders who are both technical and non-technical. In Task 2, delivery times under uncertain traffic conditions are predicted using Monte Carlo simulation and random number generation. A payoff table analysis is used to further investigate game theory. In Task 3, Yellowstone Inc.'s logistics procedures are represented and designed at both an operational and system design level using Petri nets and UML modelling. When taken as a whole, these activities provide a thorough understanding of simulation as a theoretical field and a useful business tool, showing how data-driven modelling can directly assist and enhance Yellowstone Inc.'s decision-making.



#Task 1: Understanding Simulation and Data Types
The process of creating a model of an actual system in order to understand its behaviour and analyse different approaches is known as simulation (Banks et al., 2010). In reality, simulation produces a summary or digital twin of a real-world system, enabling experts to test various scenarios without interfering with real-world operations.  Simulation is the process of creating a model of an actual system and testing it in order to understand its behaviour and forecast approaches.

Simulation is crucial in a business because it allows organisations to evaluate the potential outcomes of choices before allocating resources. Without interfering with live operations, Yellowstone Inc. can use simulation to test delivery route strategies, model warehouse workflows and forecast how traffic variations will affect delivery times.

There are a variety of simulation types that are appropriate for various problems. Systems whose conditions change at discrete points in time are modelled using Discrete-Event Simulation (DES). Continuous simulation simulates differential equation driven systems with constantly changing state parameters. Systems are shown by Agent-Based Simulation (ABS) as groups of independent agents with distinct behaviours. To model systems, Monte Carlo simulation is utilised for repeated random sampling. System Dynamics (SD) uses stocks, flows and feedback loops to simulate how complex systems behave over time.


