Payoff Table and Nash Equilibrium
In my report, I also use game theory to analyse a strategic routing choice between Redstone Logistics, a rival supplier, and Yellowstone Inc. A Standard Route (S) or an Express Route (E) must be selected independently by both businesses. Payoffs are expressed as daily profits in thousands of pounds.

Yellowstone / Redstone	Standard (S)	Express (E)
Standard (S)	(5, 5)	(3, 8)
Express (E)	(8, 3)	(6, 6) ★ 
Table 3b: Payoff Table — (Yellowstone Inc. Profit, Redstone Logistics Profit) . ★ = Nash Equilibrium

When neither player can increase their payoff by unilaterally altering their strategy, there is a Nash equilibrium (Nash, 1950). Yellowstone prefers Express (E) at £8,000 over £5,000 if Redstone plays Standard (S). Yellowstone still prefers Express (E) at £6,000 over £3,000 if Redstone plays Express (E). Therefore, Express is Yellowstone’s dominant strategy regardless of what Redstone does. By symmetric reasoning, Express is also Redstone’s dominant strategy, producing a dominant strategy equilibrium at (Express, Express) = (£6,000, £6,000). Importantly, this outcome is also socially optimal: joint profits at (Express, Express) total £12,000, which exceeds the £10,000 joint profit under (Standard, Standard). Both firms are therefore individually and collectively better off choosing Express, confirming that the dominant strategy equilibrium is both stable and efficient. This result supports Yellowstone Inc.’s strategic case for investing in express delivery infrastructure, as rational self-interest and collective welfare align in favour of the Express route.



#Task 3: Process Modelling and UML
3.1: Process Modelling with Petri Nets
Petri nets are a formal mathematical modelling language used to describe and analyse systems with resource sharing, concurrency and synchronisation (Peterson, 1977). Originally proposed by Carl Adam Petri in his 1962 doctoral dissertation, the model uses a bipartite directed graph consisting of two node types — places and transitions — connected by directed arcs to represent the dynamic behaviour of a system (Murata, 1989). Tokens (filled dots) show the current state of the system, places (circles) represent conditions or states, and transitions (rectangles) represent events or activities. A transition fires when all its input places contain the required number of tokens, consuming those tokens and depositing new ones into the output places, thereby advancing the system state.Petri nets are especially useful for Yellowstone Inc. because the package delivery process involves sequential dependencies, concurrent activities and resource limitations that are difficult to capture with simpler flowchart models. Unlike basic flowcharts, Petri nets can explicitly model parallelism — for instance, while one vehicle is being loaded, a second sorting operation can proceed independently — and can detect deadlocks, where two or more processes block each other indefinitely waiting for resources that will never become available (Reisig, 1985).
In the context of Yellowstone Inc., the Petri net model spans five places (P1–P5) and four transitions (T1–T4), tracking a package from order receipt through sorting, vehicle loading, dispatch, and final delivery confirmation. The initial marking assigns one token to P1, representing a newly received order. As each transition fires sequentially, the token advances through the network until it reaches P5 (delivered), signalling successful completion. If transition T1 (Sort Package) fires significantly more slowly than T2 (Load Vehicle), tokens accumulate in P2, identifying the sorting stage as a bottleneck. This analytical capability makes Petri nets a powerful diagnostic tool, enabling Yellowstone Inc.'s operations team to justify targeted investments such as additional sorting infrastructure or parallel processing lanes to improve overall throughput.

