Figure 1: Petri Net Diagram — Sequential Token Flow for Yellowstone Inc. Package Delivery

Sequential transition firing is modelled by the Petri net. T1 fires when P1 holds a token (order received), depositing a token in P2 (package sorted). T2 fires when P2 holds a token, enabling T3 once P3 is populated; and so on. Our analysis of the model shows that packages develop in P2, indicating a sorting capacity limit, if sorting transition T1 is much slower than loading transition T2. Targeted improvements like more sorting machines or parallel sorting lines are made possible by this insight.



 3.2: UML for System Design
Software engineers use the Unified Modelling Language (UML), a standard general-purpose modelling language, to define, visualise, build and record the components of a software-intensive system (Booch, Rumbaugh and Jacobson, 2005). Standardised by the Object Management Group (OMG) in 1997, UML has become the industry benchmark for communicating system architecture across technical and non-technical audiences alike (Fowler, 2004). The different types of UML diagrams include use case, class, sequence, activity and state diagrams, each capturing a distinct perspective on the system under design. Use case diagrams focus on functional requirements and actor interactions, class diagrams represent the static data structure, and sequence diagrams illustrate the time-ordered exchange of messages between components.
In the context of Yellowstone Inc., the package tracking system is modelled using a UML use case diagram, defining the interactions between the system's primary functions and its four key actors — customers, delivery drivers, warehouse staff and system administrators — alongside the external Notification Service. By capturing these interactions visually before any development begins, UML enables early requirements validation, reducing the risk of costly changes later in the software development lifecycle (Rumbaugh, Jacobson and Booch, 2004).
The diagram incorporates two important UML stereotyped relationships. The «include» relationship between Track Package and Send Notification indicates that every tracking event unconditionally triggers a notification, making it mandatory behaviour embedded within the base use case. The «extend» relationship between Update Delivery Status and Notify Delay represents conditional behaviour — the notification only fires when the driver explicitly marks a delivery as delayed, extending the base use case only under that specific circumstance. This distinction is significant for system design, as it directly informs how the notification engine at Yellowstone Inc. should be architected — separating mandatory from optional logic reduces coupling and makes the system easier to maintain and scale as delivery volumes grow.




