Every package tracking event starts a customer notification, which is modelled as required behaviour, according to the "include" relationship between Track Package and Send Notification. Update Delivery Status and Notify Customer of Delay have a "extend" relationship, which means that the notification is conditional and only happens when the driver marks a delivery as delayed. According to our research, Yellowstone Inc. can build the package tracking system around actual user needs by using UML, which lowers the possibility of expensive requirement changes during development.



 #Conclusion
The thorough application of simulation techniques to Yellowstone Inc.'s operational challenges has been demonstrated in my report. A variety of simulation techniques, tools and modelling approaches have been explored and applied to actual business decision-making situations across three related tasks.


Task 1 defined simulation as a powerful modelling technique that allows organisations to test plans and predict results. In a logistics context, Discrete-event, continuous, agent-based, Monte Carlo and system dynamics were analysed and the important part that visualisation plays in enabling decision-makers to access simulation outputs.

Task 2 established the theoretical foundations of random number generation. Our Monte Carlo simulation applied to Yellowstone Inc.'s delivery times, assuming a Normal distribution with μ = 30 minutes and σ = 5 minutes, showed that roughly 2.37% of deliveries are expected to exceed the 40-minute SLA limit, giving management a measurable risk estimate. In the routing strategy game between Redstone Logistics and Yellowstone Inc., game theory analysis further revealed that (Express, Express) is the Nash Equilibrium.


In Task 3, the sequential and concurrent phases of Yellowstone Inc.'s package delivery process were modelled using Petri nets, which produced a formal, analysable representation that could spot obstacles and deadlocks.

When combined, these methods give Yellowstone Inc. a strong analytical toolkit for enhancing operational effectiveness, controlling uncertainty and creating superior information systems. Future research could use agent-based modelling to simulate fleet paths under dynamic, real-time conditions, apply SimPy-based discrete-event simulation to model the entire warehouse to door delivery process and expand the Monte Carlo model to include irregular distributions derived from real-world traffic data.



